Exercise 1. What is the class of this three objects

class(tree_boots)
## [1] "phylo"
class(df_inode_data)
## [1] "data.frame"
class(df_tip_data)
## [1] "data.frame"
typeof(tree_boots)
## [1] "list"
typeof(df_inode_data)
## [1] "list"
typeof(df_tip_data)
## [1] "list"

The class of tree_boots is phylogeny. The class of df_inode_data is data frame. The class of df_tip_data is data frame.

  1. How many elements does tree_boots has
str(tree_boots)
## List of 5
##  $ edge       : int [1:12, 1:2] 8 9 10 10 9 11 11 8 12 12 ...

##  $ node.label : chr [1:6] "Mammalia" "Artiodactyla" "Cervidae" "Bovidae" ...
##  $ tip.label  : chr [1:7] "Rangifer_tarandus" "Cervus_elaphus" "Bos_taurus" "Ovis_orientalis" ...
##  - attr(*, "class")= chr "phylo"
##  - attr(*, "order")= chr "cladewise"

The number of elements in tree_boots is 12.

  1. How many rows does df_tip_data and df_inode_data have.
nrow(df_tip_data)
## [1] 7
nrow(df_inode_data)
## [1] 6

The number of rows in df_tip_data is 7. The number of rows in df_inode_data is 6.

  1. Compare the row numbers of both objects to the lengths of the $tip.label and $node.label elements of tree_boots
length(tree_boots$tip.label)
## [1] 7
length(tree_boots$node.label)
## [1] 6
tree_boots$tip.label %>% length()
## [1] 7
tree_boots$node.label %>% length()
## [1] 6

The length of the $tip.label element of tree_boots is 7. This is the same as the number of rows in df_tip_data. This means that there is a relationship between these two. Each tip label has data The length of the $node.label element of tree_boots is 6. This is the same as the number of rows in df_inode_data.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
species <- read.csv("../data-raw/species.csv")
surveys <- read.csv("../data-raw/surveys.csv")

taxonomy_means <- full_join(surveys, species) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(weight) & !is.na(hindfoot_length)) %>% 
  group_by(species_id) %>% 
  summarise(mean_weight = mean(weight), mean(hindfoot_length))
## Joining, by = "species_id"
